\begin_layout Description

\family sans
TIFF
\family default
:
 
\series bold
T
\series default
agged 
\series bold
I
\series default
mage 
\series bold
F
\series default
ile 
\series bold
F
\series default
ormat:
 raster image format which supports lossless compression.
 A .TIFF is organized by its metadata which is embedded as a sequence of 
\series bold
Image File Directories (IFDs) 
\series default
using tag-value pairs.
 Abstractly,
 a .TIFF is a function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I:\mathbb{Z}^{2}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{C}
\]

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I(x,y)$
\end_inset

 gives us a pixel value at coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\mathbb{Z}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with value 
\begin_inset Formula $(r_{1},...,r_{c})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is the number of chanels (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{RGB}\rightarrow C=3$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{grayscale}\rightarrow C=1$
\end_inset

,
 etc).
 We call this space 
\series bold
raster space
\series default
,
 or the space defined by a coordinate system and cooresponding data channels.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\family sans
IFD
\family default
:
 A section or subfile within a file to hold the bytes of an encoded image along with its metadata.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\family sans
GeoTIFF
\family default
:
 TIFF format that includes goegraphic metadata which supports accurate lat-long placement and cardinal orientation.
 This geographic space,
 or map space,
 consisting of a scale,
 orientation,
 and spatial location,
 is herein refered to as model space
\series bold
.

\series default
 This format includes the standard TIFF structure along with georeferencing tags such as:
\begin_inset Newline linebreak
\end_inset


\series bold
- 
\family sans
GeoKeyDirectoryTag
\family default
\series default
:
 defines the 
\series bold
model space
\series default
 and contains CRS information which defines the coordinate space,
 how earth position is represented,
 units,
 axis order,
 and geodetic data.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
- 
\family sans
TiepointTag
\family default
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{r},y_{r},z_{r},X_{m},Y_{m},Y_{m})$
\end_inset

:
 maps raster space 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{r},y_{r},z_{r})$
\end_inset

 to model space
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{m},Y_{m},Z_{m})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

- 
\family sans
PixelScaleTag
\family default
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma_{x},\sigma_{y},\sigma_{z})$
\end_inset

:
 defines pixel size in model units.
 This is an x-scale 
\begin_inset Formula $(\text{\ensuremath{\sigma_{x}}})$
\end_inset

 y-scale 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma_{y})$
\end_inset

 (and z-scale) corresponding to the pixel width and height respective (e.g.
 if one pixel corresponds to 50cm in model space then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma_{x}=\sigma_{y}=50,\sigma_{z}=0)$
\end_inset

 )
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 A GeoTIFF defines a spatial mapping:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T:\mathbb{Z}^{2}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T(x,y)=(x_{geo},y_{geo})=A\cdot\begin{pmatrix}x\\
y\\
1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an affine transformation matrix (preserves lines and parallelism) which translates pixel coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 in raster space to map coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{geo},y_{geo})$
\end_inset

 in model space.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0},Y_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the coordinates of the top-left pixel 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

 in model space,
 the standard definition of this transformation is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A:=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\sigma_{x} & 0 & X_{0}\\
0 & -\sigma_{y} & Y_{0}\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

So given a pixel 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 in the raster we can calculate the position of that pixel in model space:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T(x,y) & =\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\sigma_{x} & 0 & X_{0}\\
0 & -\sigma_{y} & Y_{0}\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right)\cdot\begin{pmatrix}x\\
y\\
1
\end{pmatrix}=(x_{geo},y_{geo})\\
x_{geo} & =X_{0}+x\sigma_{x}\\
y_{geo} & =Y_{0}-y\sigma_{y}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 for example,
 if 
\family sans
\series bold
TiepointTag
\family default

\begin_inset Formula $=(0,0,0,500000,4500000,0)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
and 
\family sans
\series bold
PixelScaleTag
\family default
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $=(50,50,0)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
50 & 0 & 500000\\
0 & -50 & 4500000\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and the pixel 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)$
\end_inset

 maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $(50000,4499950)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\family sans
COG
\family default
:

\series bold
 C
\series default
loud 
\series bold
O
\series default
ptimized 
\series bold
G
\series default
eoTIFFs- a georeferenced raster imagery format specifically designed for web.
 It consists of a regular GeoTIFF that has been optimized for use in a cloud based environment such as a web server or a cloud storage service.
 The key feature is a build-in organization that allows the client to access parts of the image as needed,
 without having to download the entire file.
\end_layout

